Note: ============================================================================
Note: LIR Core Type Definitions
Note: Using TIER 3 (OWNED HEAP) allocation - permanent structures during codegen
Note: All sizes calculated based on 64-bit pointers (8 bytes each)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
LIRBasicBlock represents a maximal sequence of LIR instructions with single
entry and exit points. Unlike MIR basic blocks which track SSA phi nodes,
LIR blocks have no SSA properties - registers are mutable.

Each block is labeled for assembly generation and tracks predecessors/successors
for control flow graph maintenance. Live-in and live-out register sets are
computed during liveness analysis for register allocation.
@End Reasoning

Type called "LIRBasicBlock":
    block_id as Integer                   Note: Unique block identifier
    label as Integer                      Note: Pointer to label string (e.g., ".L1")
    instructions as Integer               Note: Pointer to List of instruction pointers
    instruction_count as Integer          Note: Number of instructions in block
    predecessors as Integer               Note: Pointer to List of predecessor block IDs
    predecessor_count as Integer          Note: Number of predecessors
    successors as Integer                 Note: Pointer to List of successor block IDs
    successor_count as Integer            Note: Number of successors
    live_in as Integer                    Note: Pointer to set of live-in virtual registers
    live_out as Integer                   Note: Pointer to set of live-out virtual registers
    loop_depth as Integer                 Note: Nesting depth in loops (0 if not in loop)
    is_loop_header as Integer             Note: Boolean: 1 if loop header, 0 otherwise
End Type

Note: Size: 12 fields * 8 bytes = 96 bytes per LIRBasicBlock

@Reasoning
StackFrame tracks the stack layout for a function including local variables,
spill slots for register allocation, and arguments passed on the stack.

The frame is divided into regions with specific purposes:
- Local variables: function-local storage
- Spill slots: storage when registers are exhausted
- Call arguments: space for outgoing function call arguments
- Saved registers: callee-saved registers that must be preserved

Frame pointer (RBP) and stack pointer (RSP) management is handled based on
whether the function uses a frame pointer. Stack alignment (typically 16 bytes
on x86-64) is maintained for platform ABI compliance.
@End Reasoning

Type called "StackFrame":
    frame_size as Integer                 Note: Total frame size in bytes (aligned)
    local_area_size as Integer            Note: Size of local variable area
    spill_area_size as Integer            Note: Size of spill slot area
    arg_area_size as Integer              Note: Size of outgoing argument area
    alignment as Integer                  Note: Required stack alignment (typically 16)
    uses_frame_pointer as Integer         Note: Boolean: 1 if uses RBP, 0 if leaf function
    callee_saved_regs as Integer          Note: Pointer to List of callee-saved register IDs
    callee_saved_count as Integer         Note: Number of callee-saved registers
    local_offsets as Integer              Note: OrderedMap local ID -> stack offset (integer keys; Dictionary string-hashes keys)
    spill_offsets as Integer              Note: OrderedMap virtual reg -> spill offset (integer keys; Dictionary string-hashes keys)
End Type

Note: Size: 10 fields * 8 bytes = 80 bytes per StackFrame

@Reasoning
LIRFunction represents a complete function in LIR form ready for register
allocation and native code generation. It owns the control flow graph (CFG),
all basic blocks, the stack frame layout, and virtual register information.

Unlike MIR which operates in SSA form, LIR uses virtual registers that will
be mapped to physical registers during register allocation. Virtual register
IDs start from 1000 to distinguish them from physical register IDs (0-31).

The function tracks calling convention, whether it's external (declaration only),
and maintains metadata for debugging and optimization.
@End Reasoning

Type called "LIRFunction":
    name as Integer                       Note: Pointer to function name string
    mangled_name as Integer               Note: Pointer to mangled name for linking
    entry_block as Integer                Note: Pointer to entry basic block
    exit_block as Integer                 Note: Pointer to exit basic block
    blocks as Integer                     Note: Pointer to List of all basic blocks
    block_count as Integer                Note: Number of blocks
    parameters as Integer                 Note: Pointer to List of parameter register IDs
    parameter_count as Integer            Note: Number of parameters
    return_type as Integer                Note: Pointer to HIRTypeInfo for return type
    stack_frame as Integer                Note: Pointer to StackFrame
    virtual_reg_count as Integer          Note: Number of virtual registers
    next_vreg_id as Integer               Note: Counter for generating unique virtual reg IDs
    next_label_id as Integer              Note: Counter for generating unique label IDs
    calling_convention as Integer         Note: Calling convention constant (SYSTEMV, WIN64, etc.)
    is_external as Integer                Note: Boolean: 1 if external function, 0 if defined
    is_leaf as Integer                    Note: Boolean: 1 if leaf function (no calls)
    hir_node as Integer                   Note: Pointer to original HIR process definition
    metadata as Integer                   Note: Optional metadata pointer
    library_name as Integer               Note: P2-D FFI: Pointer to library name string (0 if not external)
    alias_name as Integer                 Note: P2-D FFI: Pointer to C-side symbol (0 if same as name)
    convention_id as Integer              Note: P2-D FFI: Calling convention ID (0=c, 1=stdcall, 2=fastcall, 3=cdecl, 4=syscall, 5=objc)
    live_ranges as Integer                Note: Task #473: OrderedMap vreg_id -> flat segment List (block_id, start, end triples), written by liveness.compute_live_ranges (0 until computed)
End Type

Note: Size: 22 fields * 8 bytes = 176 bytes per LIRFunction
Note: P2-D extension: library_name (offset 144), alias_name (offset 152), convention_id (offset 160)
Note: Task #473 extension: live_ranges (offset 168). The metadata slot at offset 136
Note: is OWNED by the Wave 5b vreg-class OrderedMap (key 1 -> vreg_classes map) and
Note: must never be overloaded with liveness results; live ranges live at 168.

@Reasoning
LIRModule is the top-level container for all LIR functions in a compilation unit.
It owns all functions, manages global initialization code, and maintains linkage
information for external symbols.

The module serves as the root for the LIR representation passed to the backend
for register allocation and native code generation.
@End Reasoning

Type called "LIRModule":
    name as Integer                       Note: Pointer to module name string
    functions as Integer                  Note: Pointer to List of LIRFunction pointers
    function_count as Integer             Note: Number of functions
    external_functions as Integer         Note: Pointer to List of external function names
    external_count as Integer             Note: Number of external functions
    global_init_block as Integer          Note: Pointer to global initialization code block
    target_triple as Integer              Note: Pointer to target triple string (e.g., "x86_64-linux-gnu")
    hir_program as Integer                Note: Pointer to original HIR program
End Type

Note: Size: 8 fields * 8 bytes = 64 bytes per LIRModule

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LIR Virtual Register Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Creates a new virtual register for use during LIR construction. Virtual registers
start at ID 1000 to distinguish from physical registers (0-31).

Register size determines allocation constraints (8, 16, 32, 64 bits).
Register class determines which physical registers can be allocated (GPR, FPR, VEC).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. NULL-guard the function pointer; emit a diagnostic and return 0 on failure.
2. Load the next_vreg_id counter at offset 88 (starts at 1000 from lir_create_function).
3. Increment next_vreg_id in place so subsequent calls allocate unique IDs.
4. Maintain the virtual_reg_count statistic at offset 80 for downstream allocator sizing.
5. Lazily materialize the per-function metadata OrderedMap at offset 136 on first
   virtual-register creation to avoid the allocation when no metadata is used.
6. Within metadata, key 1 maps to the vreg_classes OrderedMap; create it on demand.
7. Record vreg_id -> reg_class so lir_get_virtual_register_class achieves O(1) lookup
   without scanning every instruction for the defining write.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Hot path during LIR builder execution. Pure integer arithmetic plus at most two
lazy OrderedMap creations (amortized to one creation pair across an entire
function). The per-vreg insert is a single omap_set, which OrderedMap
implements as a hashed slot write on raw integer keys. Avoid materializing metadata before the first
vreg is created so leaf accessor functions stay allocation-free.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-guard on function pointer prevents memory faults on malformed builder use.
vreg_id values cannot wrap into the physical register range (0-31) within the
lifetime of any realistic compilation unit (start=1000, 64-bit counter), so the
virtual/physical discriminator is preserved by construction.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_create_virtual_register" that takes function as Integer, reg_class as Integer, reg_size as Integer returns Integer:
    If function is equal to 0:
        Display "lir_create_virtual_register: null function"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get next virtual register ID
    Let next_vreg_offset be 88
    Let vreg_id be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with function, next_vreg_offset

    Note: Increment virtual register counter
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with function, next_vreg_offset, vreg_id plus 1

    Note: Increment virtual register count
    Let vreg_count_offset be 80
    Let vreg_count be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with function, vreg_count_offset
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with function, vreg_count_offset, vreg_count plus 1

    Note: Store register class in metadata. The metadata map and the per-vreg
    Note: class map are keyed by INTEGERS (metadata key 1, vreg ids).
    Note: collections/dictionary string-hashes its keys, so integer keys are
    Note: dereferenced as string pointers and crash at runtime - integer-keyed
    Note: maps must use collections/ordered_map.
    Let metadata be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with function, 136
    If metadata is equal to 0:
        Set metadata to proc omap_create from OrderedMap
        proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with function, 136, metadata
    End If

    Note: Get or create the vreg_classes map in metadata
    Let vreg_classes be proc omap_get from OrderedMap with metadata, 1  Note: key=1 for vreg_classes
    If vreg_classes is equal to 0:
        Set vreg_classes to proc omap_create from OrderedMap
        proc omap_set from OrderedMap with metadata, 1, vreg_classes
    End If

    Note: Store register class for this virtual register
    proc omap_set from OrderedMap with vreg_classes, vreg_id, reg_class

    Return vreg_id
End Process

@Reasoning
Checks if a register ID represents a virtual register (ID > or equal to 1000) versus
a physical register (ID < 1000). Virtual registers must be allocated to
physical registers during register allocation.
@End Reasoning

Process called "lir_is_virtual_register" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If reg_id is greater than or equal to 1000:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Checks if a register ID represents a physical register (ID < 1000).
Physical registers are directly used in machine code generation.
@End Reasoning

Process called "lir_is_physical_register" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If reg_id is less than 1000:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the register class for any register ID (physical or virtual).

Physical register ID ranges:
- 0-15: GPR (general-purpose)
- 16-31: FPR (floating-point XMM)
- 32-63: VEC (vector YMM/ZMM, future)
- 64: FLAGS (RFLAGS register)

Virtual registers (>= 1000): Retrieves class from metadata stored during
creation by lir_create_virtual_register. This is O(1) lookup.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Pure ID-range classification. The two-argument form has no access to the
defining function and therefore cannot reach the vreg metadata table; it
returns LIR_REGCLASS_GPR as the default for virtual IDs. Callers that need
the true virtual class must invoke lir_get_virtual_register_class with the
owning function pointer so the metadata table can be consulted.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Branch-predicted constant comparisons only; no memory traffic. Suitable for
use in hot register-allocator inner loops when classifying physical
registers.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Negative IDs are coerced to GPR rather than asserted, on the assumption that
they originate from sentinel values inside the builder. Callers must treat
the GPR default for virtual IDs as informational, not authoritative.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_get_register_class" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If reg_id is less than 0:
        Return LIR_REGCLASS_GPR
    End If

    Note: Physical registers - classify by ID range
    If reg_id is less than 16:
        Return LIR_REGCLASS_GPR
    End If

    If reg_id is less than 32:
        Return LIR_REGCLASS_FPR
    End If

    If reg_id is less than 64:
        Return LIR_REGCLASS_VEC
    End If

    If reg_id is equal to 64:
        Return LIR_REGCLASS_FLAGS
    End If

    Note: Virtual registers - must pass function to retrieve class from metadata
    Note: This version takes only reg_id, so we return GPR as default
    Note: Use lir_get_virtual_register_class(function, reg_id) for proper lookup
    Return LIR_REGCLASS_GPR
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the register class for a virtual register by looking it up in the
function's metadata. This is the proper O(1) lookup for virtual register classes.

Virtual registers have their class stored when created by lir_create_virtual_register.
This avoids expensive instruction scanning and is the production-grade approach.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. If function is NULL, fall back to the GPR default since no metadata is reachable.
2. For physical IDs (<1000) delegate to lir_get_register_class for range-based
   classification rather than duplicating the bookkeeping.
3. Otherwise load the metadata OrderedMap at offset 136, key 1, and probe the
   vreg_classes child OrderedMap for the vreg_id entry inserted by
   lir_create_virtual_register.
4. Any miss (missing metadata, missing child table, or absent key) returns the
   GPR default rather than failing the compilation.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two omap_get calls in the worst case for virtual IDs; physical IDs
skip both. The two-level table is intentional - the outer key (1) keeps
room for future metadata categories on the same OrderedMap without changing
offset 136.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only. Defends against missing metadata by returning a safe default
register class. Does not propagate raw OrderedMap errors to the caller.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_get_virtual_register_class" that takes function as Integer, vreg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If function is equal to 0:
        Return LIR_REGCLASS_GPR  Note: Default if no function
    End If

    Note: If physical register, use ID-based classification
    If vreg_id is less than 1000:
        Return lir_get_register_class(vreg_id)
    End If

    Note: Retrieve metadata
    Let metadata be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with function, 136
    If metadata is equal to 0:
        Return LIR_REGCLASS_GPR  Note: Default if no metadata
    End If

    Note: Get vreg_classes map (integer-keyed OrderedMap; see
    Note: lir_create_virtual_register for the representation rationale)
    Let vreg_classes be proc omap_get from OrderedMap with metadata, 1  Note: key=1 for vreg_classes
    If vreg_classes is equal to 0:
        Return LIR_REGCLASS_GPR  Note: Default if not found
    End If

    Note: Lookup register class for this virtual register
    Let reg_class be proc omap_get from OrderedMap with vreg_classes, vreg_id
    If reg_class is equal to 0:
        Return LIR_REGCLASS_GPR  Note: Default if not found
    End If

    Return reg_class
End Process

@Reasoning
Checks if a physical register is callee-saved (must be preserved across calls).

System V x86-64 callee-saved registers:
- RBX, RBP, R12, R13, R14, R15 (GPR)

Win64 callee-saved registers:
- RBX, RBP, RDI, RSI, R12, R13, R14, R15 (GPR)
- XMM6-XMM15 (FPR)

This function uses System V convention. Calling convention is specified
in LIRFunction for platform-specific handling.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Linear equality compare against the System V callee-saved register IDs
(RBX, RBP, R12-R15). Returns 1 on the first match, 0 otherwise. The
sequence of If chains is intentionally flat to keep the bootstrap parse
fast and the call boundary trivial; the cost is dominated by the caller's
loop, not by branch prediction here.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Six compare-and-branch operations in the worst case; no memory accesses.
For Win64 convention queries, use platform-specific dispatch through
LIRFunction.calling_convention before reaching this accessor.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure function. No side effects, no memory access, no calling-convention
metadata required.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_is_callee_saved_register" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: System V x86-64 callee-saved registers
    If reg_id is equal to LIR_REG_RBX:
        Return 1
    End If
    If reg_id is equal to LIR_REG_RBP:
        Return 1
    End If
    If reg_id is equal to LIR_REG_R12:
        Return 1
    End If
    If reg_id is equal to LIR_REG_R13:
        Return 1
    End If
    If reg_id is equal to LIR_REG_R14:
        Return 1
    End If
    If reg_id is equal to LIR_REG_R15:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: All other registers are caller-saved
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Checks if a physical register is allocatable (available for allocation).
Some registers are reserved for special purposes:
- RSP: stack pointer (never allocatable)
- RBP: frame pointer (allocatable only if no frame pointer used)

All other physical registers are allocatable.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
RSP is hard-blocked because the ABI relies on its meaning for every call,
return, and exception frame. Physical IDs 0-31 (GPR + XMM) are otherwise
allocatable; the RBP-as-frame-pointer policy is enforced by the allocator
against StackFrame.uses_frame_pointer rather than here. Virtual registers
(>= 1000) are always candidates.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Three short branches. Inlinable into the register allocator's candidate
filter without a separate call boundary in practice.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Read-only. Provides the allocator with a conservative allowlist; rejects
unknown IDs (negative or in the vector-register reserved range 32-999) by
falling through to 0.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_is_allocatable_register" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: RSP is never allocatable (stack pointer)
    If reg_id is equal to LIR_REG_RSP:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: All other physical registers are allocatable
    Note: RBP allocation depends on function.uses_frame_pointer (checked by allocator)
    If reg_id is less than 32:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Virtual registers are always candidates for allocation
    If reg_id is greater than or equal to 1000:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns a human-readable name for a physical register ID.
Used for debug printing and assembly generation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Linear If-chain mapping LIR_REG_* IDs to their AT&T-syntax mnemonics.
GPRs and XMM registers each have a dedicated branch. Virtual registers
(>= 1000) format as "v<id>" so debug dumps remain readable before
register allocation lowers them to physical names. The fallback
"unknown" entry guards against malformed IDs reaching the assembler
printer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Up to 32 compare-branches per call - acceptable because this accessor
runs on the slow assembly-printing path, not in the optimizer hot loop.
Each successful branch performs a single StringCore.create_from_literal
that hands the assembler-printer an owned-heap string copy.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure read of constant integer IDs. The returned string is owned by the
caller (StringCore.create_from_literal duplicates the literal data) so
no aliasing risk exists with other register-name consumers.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_get_register_name" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: General-Purpose Registers
