@Reasoning
Returns the list of argument registers for a given calling convention and
argument index. Used during function prologue/epilogue generation and call lowering.

System V x86-64 integer argument registers: RDI, RSI, RDX, RCX, R8, R9
System V x86-64 float argument registers: XMM0-XMM7

Win64 integer argument registers: RCX, RDX, R8, R9
Win64 float argument registers: XMM0-XMM3

Arguments beyond register capacity are passed on the stack.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
The function is structured as a four-quadrant lookup keyed on
(calling_convention, is_float):
  (SYSTEMV, float)   -> XMM0..XMM7
  (SYSTEMV, integer) -> RDI, RSI, RDX, RCX, R8, R9
  (WIN64,   float)   -> XMM0..XMM3
  (WIN64,   integer) -> RCX, RDX, R8, R9
Each quadrant is an inline If-chain on arg_index for the corresponding
register set. A return of -1 signals "out of register slots - spill to
stack" and is consumed by the call-lowering layer to materialize the
shadow space or argument area.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Branch-only; no memory traffic. Called once per outgoing argument during
call lowering, which is well off the hot path of typical compilations.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure constant lookup. Unknown calling conventions fall through to the
System V default and then return -1, forcing the caller to handle the
spill case safely instead of misclassifying as a register argument.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_get_argument_register" that takes calling_convention as Integer, arg_index as Integer, is_float as Integer returns Integer:
    If calling_convention is equal to LIR_CC_SYSTEMV:
        If is_float is equal to 1:
            Note: System V float arguments: XMM0-XMM7
            If arg_index is equal to 0:
                Return LIR_REG_XMM0
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 1:
                Return LIR_REG_XMM1
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 2:
                Return LIR_REG_XMM2
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 3:
                Return LIR_REG_XMM3
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 4:
                Return LIR_REG_XMM4
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 5:
                Return LIR_REG_XMM5
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 6:
                Return LIR_REG_XMM6
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 7:
                Return LIR_REG_XMM7
            End If
            Note: Beyond XMM7, use stack
            Return -1
        Otherwise:
            Note: System V integer arguments: RDI, RSI, RDX, RCX, R8, R9
            If arg_index is equal to 0:
                Return LIR_REG_RDI
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 1:
                Return LIR_REG_RSI
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 2:
                Return LIR_REG_RDX
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 3:
                Return LIR_REG_RCX
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 4:
                Return LIR_REG_R8
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 5:
                Return LIR_REG_R9
            End If
            Note: Beyond R9, use stack
            Return -1
        End If
    End If

    If calling_convention is equal to LIR_CC_WIN64:
        Note: Win64 uses XMM0-XMM3 for float, RCX/RDX/R8/R9 for integer
        Note: Shadow space required even for register arguments
        If is_float is equal to 1:
            If arg_index is equal to 0:
                Return LIR_REG_XMM0
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 1:
                Return LIR_REG_XMM1
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 2:
                Return LIR_REG_XMM2
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 3:
                Return LIR_REG_XMM3
            End If
            Return -1
        Otherwise:
            If arg_index is equal to 0:
                Return LIR_REG_RCX
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 1:
                Return LIR_REG_RDX
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 2:
                Return LIR_REG_R8
            End If
            If arg_index is equal to 3:
                Return LIR_REG_R9
            End If
            Return -1
        End If
    End If

    Note: Default to System V
    Return -1
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the return value register for a given calling convention and type.

System V x86-64: RAX for integers, XMM0 for floats
Win64: RAX for integers, XMM0 for floats
@End Reasoning

Process called "lir_get_return_register" that takes calling_convention as Integer, is_float as Integer returns Integer:
    If is_float is equal to 1:
        Note: Both System V and Win64 use XMM0 for float returns
        Return LIR_REG_XMM0
    End If

    Note: Both System V and Win64 use RAX for integer returns
    Return LIR_REG_RAX
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns a list of all caller-saved registers that may be clobbered by a call.
Used during register allocation to insert spills before calls.

System V x86-64 caller-saved: RAX, RCX, RDX, RSI, RDI, R8, R9, R10, R11, XMM0-XMM15
Win64 caller-saved: RAX, RCX, RDX, R8, R9, R10, R11, XMM0-XMM5
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocates a fresh List and appends every caller-saved register ID for the
requested calling convention. System V exposes nine GPRs and all sixteen
XMMs as caller-saved; Win64 exposes seven GPRs and XMM0-XMM5. RBX/RBP/
R12-R15 are excluded from both as they are callee-saved. The list ordering
matches the assembly-time spill ordering used by the prologue/epilogue
generator.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Called once per call site during liveness/spill insertion. Allocates a
short List (<= 25 entries) on the OWNED HEAP. Callers may cache the
result per calling convention to avoid rebuilding on every call.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returns a freshly-allocated List owned by the caller. Modifying the
returned list does not affect future invocations.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_get_caller_saved_registers" that takes calling_convention as Integer returns Integer:
    Let caller_saved be proc list_create from List

    If calling_convention is equal to LIR_CC_SYSTEMV:
        Note: System V caller-saved GPRs
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_RAX
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_RCX
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_RDX
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_RSI
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_RDI
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_R8
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_R9
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_R10
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_R11

        Note: System V caller-saved XMM registers (all)
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM0
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM1
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM2
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM3
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM4
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM5
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM6
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM7
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM8
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM9
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM10
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM11
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM12
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM13
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM14
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM15
    Otherwise:
        Note: Win64 caller-saved GPRs
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_RAX
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_RCX
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_RDX
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_R8
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_R9
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_R10
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_R11

        Note: Win64 caller-saved XMM registers (XMM0-XMM5)
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM0
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM1
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM2
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM3
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM4
        proc append from List with caller_saved, LIR_REG_XMM5
    End If

    Return caller_saved
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LIR Function Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Creates a new LIR function with the given name and calling convention.
Initializes the function structure with empty block list and default settings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Allocate 176 bytes on the OWNED HEAP for the LIRFunction header (Tier 3).
2. Duplicate the name string so the LIR module owns its own copy independent
   of any HIR lifetime.
3. Initialize every field offset explicitly: entry/exit blocks (0), block and
   parameter Lists, return type, stack frame slot, virtual register accounting
   (next_vreg_id starts at 1000 so virtual IDs never collide with physical
   IDs 0-31), next_label_id (starts at 1 reserving 0 as the sentinel
   "no label"), calling convention, default-leaf flag (1, demoted by the
   builder when a call is appended), HIR back-pointer slot, and metadata.
4. Initialize the P2-D FFI extension trio (library_name, alias_name,
   convention_id) at offsets 144/152/160 to zero so non-external functions
   present a clean default.
5. Initialize the live_ranges slot (offset 168) to zero; liveness analysis
   populates it with an OrderedMap on demand and lir_clear_live_ranges
   releases it before any recompute.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One arena/heap allocation plus one string duplication per function. Field
initialization is a sequence of explicit 8-byte writes - no zero-fill loop -
to keep the per-function setup compact and inlinable in the LIR builder.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Failure modes (allocation failure, string duplication failure) emit a
diagnostic and return 0 so the caller can abort the compilation. No
partial-initialization escape: the struct is either fully wired or zero.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_create_function" that takes name as Integer, calling_convention as Integer, return_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let function be proc allocate from Layout with 176
    If function is equal to 0:
        Display "lir_create_function: allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Copy function name
    Let name_copy be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with name
    If name_copy is equal to 0:
        Display "lir_create_function: name duplication failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize function fields
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with function, 0, name_copy               Note: name
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with function, 8, 0                       Note: mangled_name (set later)
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with function, 16, 0                      Note: entry_block (set later)
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with function, 24, 0                      Note: exit_block (set later)

    Note: Create blocks list
    Let blocks be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with function, 32, blocks                 Note: blocks
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with function, 40, 0                      Note: block_count

    Note: Create parameters list
    Let parameters be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with function, 48, parameters             Note: parameters
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with function, 56, 0                      Note: parameter_count

