@Reasoning
get_has_return reports whether an LIRFunction produces a value. The
function record carries its return type as an HIRTypeInfo pointer at
offset 64; the MIR-to-LIR lowering propagates 0 for procedures that
return nothing (lir_create_function stores the pointer verbatim), so
pointer presence is the canonical value/no-value discriminator at the
LIR level. The WASM backend consumes this to decide whether to emit a
"(result i32)" clause in the function type; other backends can use it
to decide whether a return-value register must be populated before the
epilogue.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. NULL-guard the function pointer; report 0 (no return value).
2. Load the return_type pointer at offset 64.
3. Return 1 when the pointer is non-zero, 0 otherwise. The boolean
   normalization (rather than returning the raw pointer) keeps call
   sites comparing against 1 correct on every architecture.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One memory load plus one compare. Inlinable.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe defensive load. The return_type pointer is never dereferenced
here, so a stale pointer cannot cause a fault in this accessor; it is
only tested for presence.
@End Security_Scope

