    If function is equal to 0:
        Display "lir_create_stack_frame: null function"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let frame be proc allocate from Layout with 80
    If frame is equal to 0:
        Display "lir_create_stack_frame: allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize frame fields
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 0, 0                          Note: frame_size (computed later)
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 8, 0                          Note: local_area_size
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 16, 0                         Note: spill_area_size
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 24, 0                         Note: arg_area_size
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 32, 16                        Note: alignment (16 bytes for x86-64)
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 40, 1                         Note: uses_frame_pointer (default true)

    Let callee_saved_regs be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 48, callee_saved_regs         Note: callee_saved_regs
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 56, 0                         Note: callee_saved_count

    Note: Both offset maps are keyed by INTEGERS (local ids, vreg ids).
    Note: collections/dictionary string-hashes its keys, so integer keys are
    Note: dereferenced as string pointers and crash at runtime - integer-keyed
    Note: maps must use collections/ordered_map (task #473).
    Let local_offsets be proc omap_create from OrderedMap
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 64, local_offsets             Note: local_offsets

    Let spill_offsets be proc omap_create from OrderedMap
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 72, spill_offsets             Note: spill_offsets

    Note: Set frame in function
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with function, 72, frame

    Return frame
End Process

@Reasoning
Allocates a spill slot in the stack frame for a virtual register.
Returns the stack offset (negative, relative to RBP).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. NULL-guard the function and reach the stack frame via offset 72;
   surface a diagnostic when no frame has been created yet.
2. Align the current spill_area_size up to the next multiple of size so
   the slot satisfies the requested alignment (size is assumed a power of
   2 by the allocator). The aligned offset before the slot is computed
   explicitly; the slot itself occupies [aligned_offset, aligned_offset +
   size).
3. Bump spill_area_size in the frame to reserve the new slot.
4. Compute the negative RBP-relative offset (slots grow downward) and
   record vreg_id -> stack_offset in the spill_offsets OrderedMap at
   offset 72 of the frame so the assembly emitter can rematerialize the
   spill location.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
A handful of integer arithmetic operations plus one OrderedMap set. Called
once per spilled virtual register, which is bounded by the number of
spills inserted by the register allocator.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe; surfaces diagnostics for missing frame. Negative RBP offsets
are guaranteed by construction (the negation of a non-negative quantity)
so the returned value is always interpretable by the prologue emitter.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_allocate_spill_slot" that takes function as Integer, vreg_id as Integer, size as Integer returns Integer:
    If function is equal to 0:
        Display "lir_allocate_spill_slot: null function"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let frame_offset be 72
    Let frame be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with function, frame_offset
    If frame is equal to 0:
        Display "lir_allocate_spill_slot: no stack frame"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get current spill area size
    Let spill_area_offset be 16
    Let spill_size be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, spill_area_offset

    Note: Align to size boundary (size should be power of 2)
    Let aligned_offset be spill_size
    Let remainder be aligned_offset modulo by size
    If remainder is not equal to 0:
        Set aligned_offset to aligned_offset plus (size minus remainder)
    End If

    Note: Allocate space
    Let new_spill_size be aligned_offset plus size
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, spill_area_offset, new_spill_size

    Note: Stack offset is negative from RBP
    Let stack_offset be -(aligned_offset plus size)

    Note: Record mapping (integer-keyed OrderedMap; see lir_create_stack_frame)
    Let spill_offsets be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 72
    proc omap_set from OrderedMap with spill_offsets, vreg_id, stack_offset

    Return stack_offset
End Process

@Reasoning
Finalizes the stack frame by computing total frame size with proper alignment.
Called after all local variables and spill slots are allocated.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. NULL-guard the function and resolve its stack frame (offset 72).
2. Sum local_area_size + spill_area_size + arg_area_size to get the
   variable portion of the frame.
3. Add 8 bytes per callee-saved register so the prologue's PUSH sequence
   has reserved space inside the frame.
4. Round the total up to the frame's alignment (typically 16 bytes for
   x86-64) so the post-prologue RSP is properly aligned for any callee.
5. Store the final size at offset 0 and return it for the prologue emitter.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
A constant amount of arithmetic. Called once per function during prologue
lowering. The alignment round-up uses a modulo-and-add rather than a
mask so the code remains readable when alignment is non-power-of-two on
exotic targets.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe; surfaces a diagnostic when no frame is present. Returns 0 on
failure so the prologue emitter can detect the error before generating
malformed assembly.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_finalize_stack_frame" that takes function as Integer returns Integer:
    If function is equal to 0:
        Display "lir_finalize_stack_frame: null function"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let frame_offset be 72
    Let frame be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with function, frame_offset
    If frame is equal to 0:
        Display "lir_finalize_stack_frame: no stack frame"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get area sizes
    Let local_size be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 8
    Let spill_size be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 16
    Let arg_size be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 24
    Let alignment be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 32

    Note: Calculate total size
    Let total_size be local_size plus spill_size plus arg_size

    Note: Add space for callee-saved registers
    Let callee_saved_count be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 56
    Let callee_saved_size be callee_saved_count multiplied by 8
    Set total_size to total_size plus callee_saved_size

    Note: Align total frame size
    Let remainder be total_size modulo by alignment
    If remainder is not equal to 0:
        Set total_size to total_size plus (alignment minus remainder)
    End If

    Note: Set final frame size
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with frame, 0, total_size

    Return total_size
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LIR Module Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Creates a new LIR module to contain all functions in a compilation unit.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. Allocate 64 bytes on the OWNED HEAP for the LIRModule header.
2. Duplicate the module name string so the module owns it independent of
   any HIR program lifetime.
3. Initialize the functions and external_functions Lists, zero out the
   function_count and external_count tallies, and reset the
   global_init_block, target_triple, and hir_program pointers for the
   backend driver to populate as the compilation progresses.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One module allocation, one string duplication, two List allocations.
Called once per compilation unit.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Failure modes (allocation failure, name duplication failure) surface a
diagnostic and return 0. Callers must check the return value before
populating function tables.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_create_module" that takes name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let module be proc allocate from Layout with 64
    If module is equal to 0:
        Display "lir_create_module: allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Copy module name
    Let name_copy be proc string_duplicate from StringCore with name
    If name_copy is equal to 0:
        Display "lir_create_module: name duplication failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize module fields
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with module, 0, name_copy                 Note: name

    Let functions be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with module, 8, functions                 Note: functions
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with module, 16, 0                        Note: function_count

    Let external_functions be proc list_create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with module, 24, external_functions       Note: external_functions
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with module, 32, 0                        Note: external_count

    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with module, 40, 0                        Note: global_init_block
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with module, 48, 0                        Note: target_triple (set later)
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with module, 56, 0                        Note: hir_program

    Return module
End Process

@Reasoning
Adds a function to the LIR module.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Appends the LIRFunction pointer to the module's functions List (offset 8)
and bumps function_count (offset 16). The pointer is stored verbatim - the
function continues to be owned by the module's heap subarena.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One List.append plus two memory accesses. Called once per function during
module assembly.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-guards both parameters and surfaces a diagnostic on failure without
mutating the module.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_add_function" that takes module as Integer, function as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0 or function is equal to 0:
        Display "lir_add_function: null parameter"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let functions_offset be 8
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with module, functions_offset
    proc append from List with functions, function

    Let count_offset be 16
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with module, count_offset
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with module, count_offset, count plus 1

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Retrieves a function from the module by index.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Loads the module's functions List pointer (offset 8) and function_count
(offset 16), validates the index against [0, function_count), and
delegates the indexed read to List.get. Returns 0 with a diagnostic on
any failure.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two memory loads plus one List.get. O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Bounds-checks the index against function_count to guarantee no
out-of-range read from the underlying List storage.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_get_function" that takes module as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Display "lir_get_function: null module"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let functions_offset be 8
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with module, functions_offset

    Let count_offset be 16
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with module, count_offset

    If index is less than 0 or index is greater than or equal to count:
        Display "lir_get_function: invalid index"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let function be proc list_get from List with functions, index
    Return function
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LIR Instruction Query Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
LIR carries TWO instruction record shapes in block instruction Lists:
1. Bare LIRInstruction records (create_lir_instruction, create_lir_return,
   create_lir_jump) whose opcode genuinely sits at offset 0.
2. Typed wrapper records (LIRMove, LIRBinaryOp, LIRLoad, LIRStore, LIRCall,
   LIRBranch, ...) whose offset 0 holds a POINTER to the base LIRInstruction;
   lir_builder appends these wrappers directly.
Every pass that reads opcode or operand slots must first resolve the record
to its base LIRInstruction. The discriminator is sound: opcodes occupy the
closed band [30000, 30999] while heap pointers are far outside it, so a
value in the band IS the opcode (bare record) and anything else is a base
pointer (wrapper record).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. NULL-guard; 0 resolves to 0.
2. Read the first 8-byte slot. If it lies in [30000, 30999] the record is
   already a base LIRInstruction - return it unchanged.
3. Otherwise the slot is the wrapper's base pointer. Validate that the
   pointed-to record's own offset 0 carries an in-band opcode; if it does,
   return the base pointer. If it does not, the record is malformed -
   return 0 so callers fail safely instead of reading garbage operands.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
At most two 8-byte loads and four compares. Inlinable into every
instruction-walking loop in liveness, interference, allocation, and
spilling.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Defends every downstream operand dereference against the dual-shape
instruction Lists and against malformed records (e.g. wrappers whose base
construction failed). Returning 0 on malformation converts a wild pointer
dereference into a skipped instruction plus caller-side diagnostics.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_resolve_instruction_base" that takes record as Integer returns Integer:
    If record is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let first_slot be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with record, 0

    Note: In-band opcode: the record is already a base LIRInstruction
    If first_slot is greater than or equal to 30000:
        If first_slot is less than or equal to 30999:
            Return record
        End If
    End If

    Note: Wrapper record: offset 0 holds the base LIRInstruction pointer
    If first_slot is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let base_opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with first_slot, 0
    If base_opcode is greater than or equal to 30000:
        If base_opcode is less than or equal to 30999:
            Return first_slot
        End If
    End If

    Note: Neither shape matched: malformed record
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Releases the live-range storage hanging off LIRFunction offset 168 so
liveness analysis can recompute from a clean slate without leaking the
previous OrderedMap and its per-vreg segment Lists. This is the
destructor coverage for the task #473 record-growth slot: LIRFunction has
no whole-record destructor (modules are torn down arena-style by the
driver), so the only lifecycle event for this slot is recompute, and this
function owns it.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. NULL-guard the function pointer.
2. Load the live_ranges OrderedMap at offset 168; nothing to do when 0.
3. Walk the map entries (omap_first / omap_entry_next); each entry value
   is a flat segment List owned by the map - destroy each List.
4. Destroy the OrderedMap itself and zero the slot so accessors observe
   the "not computed" state.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(number of vregs with ranges). Runs once per liveness recompute, off the
per-instruction hot path.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe at every level (function, map, entry values). Zeroing the slot
before returning prevents double-free on repeated calls.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_clear_live_ranges" that takes function as Integer returns Integer:
    If function is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let live_ranges be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with function, 168
    If live_ranges is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Destroy each per-vreg segment List owned by the map
    Let entry be proc omap_first from OrderedMap with live_ranges
    While entry is not equal to 0:
        Let segment_list be proc omap_entry_value from OrderedMap with entry
        If segment_list is not equal to 0:
            proc list_destroy from List with segment_list
        End If
        Set entry to proc omap_entry_next from OrderedMap with entry
    End While

    proc omap_destroy from OrderedMap with live_ranges
    proc memory_set_int64 from MemoryCore with function, 168, 0

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Checks if an instruction is a terminator (ends a basic block).
Terminators include: JMP, conditional branches, RET, CALL (indirect only).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Loads the opcode field at offset 0 of the LIRInstruction header and tests
it against the unconditional jump opcode, the contiguous conditional
branch range [LIR_JZ, LIR_JNP], and the return opcode. The range test
relies on the contiguous numbering in the LIR opcode table (30501-30518
for conditional branches).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One memory load plus three branches. Called from every CFG-walking pass
and the basic-block builder's "is this the last instruction" check.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe load. Unrecognized opcodes fall through to 0 (not a
terminator) so the caller's iterator continues safely past unknown
extension instructions.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_is_terminator" that takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc lir_resolve_instruction_base with instruction
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 0

    Note: Unconditional jump
    If opcode is equal to LIR_JMP:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Conditional branches
    If opcode is greater than or equal to LIR_JZ and opcode is less than or equal to LIR_JNP:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Return
    If opcode is equal to LIR_RET:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Checks if an instruction is a branch (conditional or unconditional).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Loads the opcode at offset 0 and tests for LIR_JMP plus the contiguous
range [LIR_JZ, LIR_JNP]. Distinguished from lir_is_terminator by
excluding LIR_RET so callers that specifically want intraprocedural
branches do not have to filter returns.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One memory load plus two branches. Used by every branch-folding and
target-rewriting pass.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe load. Unknown opcodes return 0.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_is_branch" that takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc lir_resolve_instruction_base with instruction
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 0

    Note: Unconditional jump
    If opcode is equal to LIR_JMP:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Conditional branches
    If opcode is greater than or equal to LIR_JZ and opcode is less than or equal to LIR_JNP:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Checks if an instruction is a call (direct or indirect).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Loads the opcode at offset 0 and matches it against LIR_CALL or
LIR_CALL_INDIRECT. Direct calls have known target symbols at lower; the
indirect form uses a register operand resolved at runtime. Both clobber
caller-saved registers and require call-site bookkeeping.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One memory load plus one branch. Used by liveness, caller-saved spill
insertion, and the leaf-function detector.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe. Returns 0 for instructions whose opcode does not match either
call form.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_is_call" that takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc lir_resolve_instruction_base with instruction
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 0

    If opcode is equal to LIR_CALL or opcode is equal to LIR_CALL_INDIRECT:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Checks if an instruction is a load from memory.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Tests the opcode against the contiguous load range
[LIR_LOAD, LIR_LOAD64]. The single range covers the generic load and
all four sized variants (LOAD8/16/32/64) so memory-aliasing passes can
classify reads with one comparison pair.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One memory load and one range test. Inlinable into alias-analysis loops.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe. Conservative: returns 0 for any opcode outside the load range.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_is_load" that takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc lir_resolve_instruction_base with instruction
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 0

    If opcode is greater than or equal to LIR_LOAD and opcode is less than or equal to LIR_LOAD64:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Checks if an instruction is a store to memory.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Tests the opcode against the contiguous store range
[LIR_STORE, LIR_STORE64]. Mirrors lir_is_load's structure so memory
classifiers can use the two accessors symmetrically.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One memory load and one range test. Hot in DCE/CSE alias filters.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_is_store" that takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc lir_resolve_instruction_base with instruction
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 0

    If opcode is greater than or equal to LIR_STORE and opcode is less than or equal to LIR_STORE64:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Checks if an instruction is a move (register-to-register or immediate-to-register).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Tests the opcode against LIR_MOV. Excludes LIR_MOVSX, LIR_MOVZX, and
LIR_CMOVcc deliberately - those have different semantics (sign extend,
zero extend, conditional) that downstream passes (move coalescing,
copy propagation) must not treat as plain copies.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One memory load and one branch.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_is_move" that takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc lir_resolve_instruction_base with instruction
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 0

    If opcode is equal to LIR_MOV:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Checks if an instruction has side effects (memory writes, calls, returns).
Instructions with side effects cannot be eliminated during dead code elimination.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Combines four checks in order of selectivity:
1. lir_is_store - any memory write is observable.
2. lir_is_call - calls clobber arbitrary state.
3. LIR_RET - the function return is the function's main side effect.
4. LIR_SYSCALL - kernel calls cross the trust boundary and must persist.
Any positive match terminates with 1; everything else is treated as
side-effect free (the DCE pass then decides eliminability via
lir_is_eliminable).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Up to four memory loads and four branches. Hot in DCE; ordering store
first matches typical instruction-mix where memory writes dominate side
effects.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Conservative by construction - any unrecognized side-effect-bearing
opcode that does not fit one of the four cases is treated as
side-effect free, which means DCE will eliminate it. Extension opcodes
that have side effects must be added here before they ship.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_has_side_effects" that takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc lir_resolve_instruction_base with instruction
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 0

    Note: Stores have side effects
    If proc lir_is_store with instruction is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Calls have side effects
    If proc lir_is_call with instruction is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Returns have side effects
    If opcode is equal to LIR_RET:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: System calls have side effects
    If opcode is equal to LIR_SYSCALL:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Checks if an instruction can be eliminated if its result is unused.
Pure computational instructions (ADD, SUB, etc.) can be eliminated.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. NULL-safe early return.
2. Reject anything with side effects (via lir_has_side_effects).
3. Reject terminators (via lir_is_terminator) because removing them would
   break the CFG.
4. Everything else is a pure computation whose result can be elided when
   no downstream user reads its definition.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Two helper calls plus comparison logic. Hot in DCE; the early-out on
side effects skips the terminator check on the common case of memory
writes.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Conservative: anything that is not provably pure and non-terminating is
kept. False negatives waste optimization opportunities but never
introduce miscompilation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_is_eliminable" that takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    If instruction is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Instructions with side effects cannot be eliminated
    If proc lir_has_side_effects with instruction is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Branches and terminators cannot be eliminated
    If proc lir_is_terminator with instruction is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Everything else can be eliminated if result is unused
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LIR Utility Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Returns a human-readable name for an LIR opcode.
Used for debug printing and error messages.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Long If-chain mapping each LIR_* opcode constant to its assembly
mnemonic via StringCore.create_from_literal. Mnemonics follow Intel/AT&T
conventions ("mov", "add", "jmp", ...). Unknown opcodes fall through
to "unknown" so debug dumps remain readable when new opcodes appear
without an entry here.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Linear branch chain. Used only by debug printing and error formatting -
not on any compile-time hot path. The owned-heap string returned to the
caller is freshly allocated on each call.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure constant lookup. The returned string is owned by the caller.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_get_opcode_name" that takes opcode as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Data Movement Operations
    If opcode is equal to LIR_NOP:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "nop"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_MOV:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "mov"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_LEA:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "lea"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_PUSH:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "push"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_POP:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "pop"
    End If

    Note: Arithmetic Operations
    If opcode is equal to LIR_ADD:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "add"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_SUB:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "sub"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_IMUL:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "imul"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_IDIV:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "idiv"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_NEG:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "neg"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_INC:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "inc"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_DEC:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "dec"
    End If

    Note: Logical Operations
    If opcode is equal to LIR_AND:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "and"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_OR:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "or"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_XOR:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "xor"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_NOT:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "not"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_TEST:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "test"
    End If

    Note: Shift Operations
    If opcode is equal to LIR_SHL:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "shl"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_SHR:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "shr"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_SAR:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "sar"
    End If

    Note: Comparison
    If opcode is equal to LIR_CMP:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "cmp"
    End If

    Note: Control Flow
    If opcode is equal to LIR_JMP:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "jmp"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_JZ:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "jz"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_JNZ:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "jnz"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_JE:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "je"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_JNE:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "jne"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_JL:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "jl"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_JLE:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "jle"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_JG:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "jg"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_JGE:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "jge"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_CALL:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "call"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_RET:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "ret"
    End If

    Note: Memory Operations
    If opcode is equal to LIR_LOAD:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "load"
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_STORE:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "store"
    End If

    Note: Special
    If opcode is equal to LIR_LABEL:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "label"
    End If

    Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "unknown"
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the size of operand based on opcode and instruction properties.
Used for proper machine code generation and memory operations.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Maps each sized load/store opcode to its operand width:
- LIR_LOAD8/LIR_STORE8   -> 1 byte
- LIR_LOAD16/LIR_STORE16 -> 2 bytes
- LIR_LOAD32/LIR_STORE32 -> 4 bytes
- LIR_LOAD64/LIR_STORE64 -> 8 bytes
All other opcodes default to 8 bytes (64-bit), the platform word size.
A NULL instruction also defaults to 8 so callers can safely query
absent slots during peephole rewriting.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
One memory load plus up to four branches. Used by the assembly emitter
when selecting load/store mnemonics and operand sizes.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe. The 8-byte default is the conservative choice: it never
under-reads or under-writes memory if the opcode classification is
incomplete.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_get_operand_size_from_instruction" that takes instruction as Integer returns Integer:
    Let base be proc lir_resolve_instruction_base with instruction
    If base is equal to 0:
        Return 8
    End If

    Let opcode be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with base, 0

    Note: Sized load/store operations have explicit size
    If opcode is equal to LIR_LOAD8 or opcode is equal to LIR_STORE8:
        Return 1
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_LOAD16 or opcode is equal to LIR_STORE16:
        Return 2
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_LOAD32 or opcode is equal to LIR_STORE32:
        Return 4
    End If
    If opcode is equal to LIR_LOAD64 or opcode is equal to LIR_STORE64:
        Return 8
    End If

    Note: Default to 8 bytes (64-bit)
    Return 8
End Process

@Reasoning
Returns the condition code name for debugging and assembly generation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Maps each LIR_COND_* code (EQ, NE, LT, LE, GT, GE, ULT, ULE, UGT, UGE) to
its textual mnemonic via StringCore.create_from_literal. The unsigned
variants are named with the "u" prefix consistent with LLVM-style
condition naming. Unknown codes fall through to "unknown" for safe debug
printing.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Linear If-chain over a fixed ten-code table. Used only by debug printing
and assembly generation.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Pure constant lookup. The returned string is owned by the caller.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_get_condition_name" that takes condition as Integer returns Integer:
    If condition is equal to LIR_COND_EQ:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "eq"
    End If
    If condition is equal to LIR_COND_NE:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "ne"
    End If
    If condition is equal to LIR_COND_LT:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "lt"
    End If
    If condition is equal to LIR_COND_LE:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "le"
    End If
    If condition is equal to LIR_COND_GT:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "gt"
    End If
    If condition is equal to LIR_COND_GE:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "ge"
    End If
    If condition is equal to LIR_COND_ULT:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "ult"
    End If
    If condition is equal to LIR_COND_ULE:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "ule"
    End If
    If condition is equal to LIR_COND_UGT:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "ugt"
    End If
    If condition is equal to LIR_COND_UGE:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "uge"
    End If

    Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "unknown"
End Process

@Reasoning
Prints the entire LIR module for debugging purposes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
1. NULL-guard the module pointer.
2. Print a fixed header banner so the dump is easy to locate in mixed
   debug output.
3. Read the module name string at offset 0 and display it followed by the
   function_count at offset 16.
4. Walk the functions List sequentially, displaying each function's name
   string. Per-instruction printing is intentionally delegated to
   lir_nodes.runa so the module printer stays compact and can be invoked
   from any pass without pulling in the full instruction printer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Linear in the function count. Only used for debugging and
post-compilation dumps - never on the compile-time hot path.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
NULL-safe; surfaces a diagnostic when the module pointer is null. Read-
only across all module fields.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "lir_print_module" that takes module as Integer returns Integer:
    If module is equal to 0:
        Display "lir_print_module: null module"
        Return 0
    End If

    Display "=== LIR Module ==="

    Let name be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with module, 0
    Display "Module: "
    Display name
    Display ""

    Let function_count be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with module, 16
    Display "Functions: "
    Display function_count
    Display ""

    Note: Print each function (detailed printing implemented in lir_nodes.runa)
    Let functions be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with module, 8
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than function_count:
        Let function be proc list_get from List with functions, i
        Display "Function "
        Display i
        Display ": "
        Let func_name be proc memory_get_int64 from MemoryCore with function, 0
        Display func_name
        Display ""
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process
